 Middle English personal name <i>Hu(gh)elot</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Hugh</i>, <i>Hue</i> (see   Hugh  ) formed with the suffixes <i>-el</i> + <i>-ot</i>. This Anglo-Norman name has also been established in Ireland (Wexford) since the 13th century, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>Húiléid</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hollett","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Howlett  ."]},{"name":"Hullett","meanings":["English (Surrey): variant of   Howlett  ."]},{"name":"Hewlett","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire and Somerset): variant of   Howlett  . This surname is also established in Ireland (mainly Tipperary)."]},{"name":"Hugh","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Scottish (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Hue</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hugo</i> (ultimately derived from <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, spirit’). This was a very popular name in England after the Norman Conquest, partly due to the reputation of Saint Hugh of Lincoln (1140–1200), who was born in Burgundy and who established the first Carthusian monastery in England.","Scottish and Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Aodh</i>, a derivative of a Gaelic word meaning ‘fire’. See   Hughes  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 邱 and 丘, based on their Hakka pronunciation; see   Qiu   1 and 2."]}]},{"name":"Agnes-","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes- Ann Howlett was born in 1529, in Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with John Warren. She died about 1560, at the age of 32."},"et":{"       1529–Abt 1560":"1529–umbes 1560","1525–1576":"1525–1576","1555–1613":"1555–1613","1529–1560":"1529–1560","Abt 1560":"umbes 1560","1613":"1613","1525":"1525","1555":"1555","1576":"1576","before 1 August 1555":"enne 1. augustit 1555","1560":"1560","1529":"1529","       1529":"1529","Corlie, Nayland, Suffolk, Eng":"Nayland, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Nayland, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"       1529–Abt 1560":"1529–noin 1560","1525–1576":"1525–1576","1555–1613":"1555–1613","1529–1560":"1529–1560","Abt 1560":"noin 1560","1613":"1613","1525":"1525","1555":"1555","1576":"1576","before 1 August 1555":"ennen vuotta 1. elokuuta 1555","1560":"1560","1529":"1529","       1529":"1529","Corlie, Nayland, Suffolk, Eng":"Nayland, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Nayland, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"       1529–Abt 1560":"1529–environ 1560","1525–1576":"1525–1576","1555–1613":"1555–1613","1529–1560":"1529–1560","Abt 1560":"environ 1560","1613":"1613","1525":"1525","1555":"1555","1576":"1576","before 1 August 1555":"avant 1 août 1555","1560":"1560","1529":"1529","       1529":"1529","Corlie, Nayland, Suffolk, Eng":"Nayland, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Nayland,